            "sentence": "Net neutrality pros and cons: what you need to know Aug 02, 2019 · 3 min read It’s been well over a year since the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) revoked net neutrality.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "sentence": "A lot has happened since, and the debate over whether net neutrality is good or bad is ongoing.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "sentence": "Net neutrality (also known as the Open Internet) is the principle that all internet connections should be treated equally.",
            "fact": true,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "sentence": "If there’s no net neutrality, internet service providers (ISPs) can discriminate against sites or services and regulate what users can and can’t see.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": true,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "sentence": "The FCC first started talking about rolling back net neutrality rules in 2017.",
            "fact": true,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "sentence": "By no longer classifying ISPs under Title II of the Communications Act of 1934, they could charge more for specific content, slow down their competitors’ services, or block internet access altogether.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": true,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "sentence": "By the end of 2017, the FCC had revoked net neutrality and allowed ISPs to sell their users’ data without their permission.",
            "fact": true,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "sentence": "In 2019, the House of Representatives attempted to reinstate net neutrality, but that effort is still underway.",
            "fact": true,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "sentence": "It significantly affects both internet users and ISPs in very different ways, so there are a lot of arguments for and against net neutrality.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "sentence": "From the consumers’ point of view, net neutrality is a guarantee that all connections are treated equally and ISPs won’t censor the internet.",
            "fact": true,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "sentence": "To ISPs, however, net neutrality means that the government will heavily control how they do their business.",
            "fact": false,
            "misinformation": false,
            "opinion": false,
            "temporal": false,
            "ignore": false,
            "sentence_category": "Uncategorized"
        },
        {
